</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AA50D858B163C7923FBB83FB26E6F3CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="E217B27F6364CF8521109E845E2DA142" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D707D9E5F4C54B55A0E2F5C3DF242E10" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The coiled, or at least sharply bent, pedicels suggest a close relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="05B073CC25C9B50BDE91FF8E84B9020C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="heptaphylla">
<emphasis id="9A0B32F21EDE4381AF220E1E8C2CDE9C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea heptaphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but this species is easily distinguished by the fimbriate outer sepals. We have not been able to examine the inner sepals or the seeds, which are not described above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
